Description: This was the strongest shock felt in the San Francisco area since 1906. Felt land area was approximately 12,000 square miles. (See map, page 195.) Magnitude 5.3. Maximum intensity VII. No lives were lost; about forty minor injuries reported. Damage of all types was estimated by engineers to be in the neighborhood of one million dollars. Principal building damage occurred to one- and two-story wood-frame houses in the Westlake Palisades tract west of Daly City along the ocean. Several dwellings in this tract sustained structural damage. The 1,600,000-gallon reinforced-concrete Westlake Palisades water reservoir (partly underground) had a 4-foot-long crack on one side extending upward from the ground. The largest of several landslides completely blocked State Highway No. 1 near Mussel Rock, and the shoulder of the highway pavement was extensively cracked. Building and dwelling damage in San Francisco was slight and consisted mainly of cracked plaster and broken windows. The road pavement (on unconsolidated soil and fill) along the southern edge of Lake Merced sloughed off into the lake, and both ends of a 200-foot-long pedestrian bridge collapsed. It was reported 2,395 emergency calls were received by plumbers, with 1,500 coming from the home areas south of Sloat Boulevard and north of the Colma cemeteries. There were 856 water heaters damaged, 125 of which required replacement; 62 toilets replaced; 175 wash basins damaged or fractured; 245 toilet tank covers broken; 173 boiler steam lines fractured or broken; 97 broken sewer lines; 422 fractured, broken or bent gas supply lines. At the Colma cemeteries some headstones fell and many were twisted. About forty-four brick chimneys at Daly City were pulled down by the fire department up to 26 March. All strong-motion seismographs in San Francisco, San Jose, and Oakland were operated by this shock, also the instrument located on the Carquinez Bridge at Martinez.

Some monuments were turned as much as 45° on a vertical axis on their stone base but were not dislodged, while other monuments were moved on their base as much as 6 inches in a westerly direction. Other monuments were toppled from the base. Ground: Sandy loam, sloping.

Description: Press reported damage in these areas was estimated by the city manager as follows: Personal belongings, $400,000; homes in Westlake Palisades, $62,500; Westlake Shopping Center, $69,000. Of the 4,000 homes in the Westlake and Westlake Palisades areas, 200 were damaged, 20 seriously. It was reported the average cost of repairs should not exceed $200, with the exception of the homes sustaining structural damage in the Westlake Palisades tract. It was reported forty-four brick chimneys were pulled down in Daly City by the fire department and that many more were probably damaged. The Westlake Reservoir, 1,600,000-gallon, 175 feet long, 108 feet wide, 23 feet deep (half submerged in the ground) had a 4-foot-long crack, extending upward from the ground, in the side of the concrete tank. The tank was to be drained to determine the extent of subsurface cracking.

For the past two years I have heard earth noises, and as time went on the acoustics in my house seemed to change. The floors used to give a little as we walked across them, making stoves, etc., rattle. Now the floors seem to be more solid and there's no more rattling, not even when cars go by. Before the big shock I felt very slight up-and-down motions like one would feel on a boat. Very loud noises heard during the big shock, and there have been several loud rumbles since. There still seems to be a throbbing sound almost constantly.

Felt as a jarring motion from W-E and up and down, then slight rocking, lasting few seconds. Buildings appeared to be bouncing. Sounds ridiculous but that's the way they looked to us.

Location: Crestmoor Park No. 2, San Bruno, CA 94066
Description: Motion rapid, lasted 6-10 seconds. Direction NE. Loud earth noises heard. Small objects and furnishings shifted. Dishes broke. Plaster cracked. Damage slight. Ground: Sloping.
Motion rapid, lasted about 3 minutes. Direction N. Loud earth noises heard. Furnishings shifted. Dishes broke. Plaster cracked. Damage slight (about $100). Ground: Compact, sloping.
Motion slow, then rapid, lasted 30-60 seconds. Direction SE-NW. Loud earth noises heard. Small objects shifted. Dishes broke. Ground: Soil, compact, level.
Motion rapid, lasted about 25 seconds. Direction N. Loud earth noises heard. Small objects shifted. Dishes broke. Damage about $100. Ground: Soil.
Motion rapid, lasted 3-4 seconds. Direction E-W. Loud earth noises heard. Small objects and furnishings shifted. Dishes and one lamp broke. Ground: Soil, compact, sloping.

Jolt from W-E, lasted about 5 seconds. Moderate earth noises heard. Small objects shifted. Small plaster cracks. Damage slight. Different motion than the shock of 1906. Would have caused much damage had it lasted longer. Ground: Compact, clay, sloping.
Dishes broke. Soil, compact, level.
Dishes broke. Soil, compact, sloping.
Few small objects shifted; one trophy broke. Ground: Compact, level; concrete slab house.

Location: Lake Merced and Harding Municipal Park area, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Highway skirting the south edge of Lake Merced cracked and sloughed off into the lake. Harding Park access road damaged. Both ends of a 200-foot-long pedestrian bridge collapsed. Sewer and gas lines to the Harding Park Golf Course broke.

Press reported buildings in San Francisco were severely shaken, but no serious damage occurred. The State Building at Folk and McAllister Streets had numerous plaster cracks, also the California Building at 515 Van Ness Avenue, where a light fixture fell on the third floor. Plaster fell from walls and ceilings in the Hall of Justice. Walls cracked and a skylight broke at the City Hall. The Presidio branch library at Sacramento near Baker was closed due to damage. The McCreery branch (built about 1903) on 16th near Market was condemned. The brick building was declared structurally unsafe. Repairs to the Presidio branch included chimney top, hanging light fixture supports, and plaster cracks. Several other branch libraries suffered damage, including the Ocean View branch at 111 Broad Street which was closed for five days. Steel book racks in the Main Library at the Civic Center moved during the shock, spewing books on the floor, but no damage was done to the building. No serious damage was reported in any of the city's hospitals. At the Mary's Help Hospital, 145 Guerrero Street, plaster was cracked and loosened on the upper floors. Loose masonry or falling mortar on upper floors caused the police to rope off areas at Post Street and Grant Avenue, at 140 Sansome Street, and at 625 Polk Street. The Seventh Day Adventist Church at 2897 California Street reported two long cracks in the steeple. Chimney fell at 3977 Clay Street and one was badly damaged at 420 Frederick Street. At Stonestown many windows were broken in one of the large apartment buildings. From the top floor of one of the 13-story Parkmerced Towers apartment building, a resident reported the building rocked and rolled, knocked all the lamps down, and cracked all the plastering. The house looks like a wreck. It was reported the top floor of St. Anne's School, 1330-14th Ave., was badly damaged. Glass was broken in more than 400 city-owned street lights, mostly along Great Highway, Sunset Boulevard, Sloat Boulevard, and Junipero Serra Boulevard. The Pacific Gas and Electric Company had similar damage in the Richmond district. The PG&E's biggest chore was reconnecting gas water heaters. Most plumbing damage occurred west of Twin Peaks, generally in the area along Nineteenth Avenue, on Sloat Boulevard, east on Ocean Avenue to San Jose Avenue, and south on San Jose Avenue to Daly City. Grocery and liquor stores in San Francisco had fairly heavy damage from bottled goods breakage. The Safeway stores at Alemany and San Jose Avenues, and on West Portal Avenue, were a shambles. Plate glass windows buckled at the Alemany Store. Store front windows were shattered along Balboa Street from 35th to 40th Avenues in the Richmond district, and on Irving Street between 20th and 23rd Avenues in the Sunset district. All front windows of the Littleman supermarket, 1630 Ocean Avenue, were broken out. It was reported light poles waved like reeds in the breeze at the Civic Center. Bells rang at St. Patrick's Church, Mission near Third Streets. A painter working on the south tower of the Golden Gate Bridge said the tower shook like a tree in a gale. The deck of the bridge galloped up and down and the suspenders (cables) slipped back and forth. He ran to get off the bridge. At least 20 windows broke at the Administration Building and Toll Plaza. Bay Bridge authorities reported no structural damage and traffic moved smoothly. But it was a real hard shake, said one employee. The Sheraton-Palace Hotel had a broken plate glass window and broken crockery. The telephone company reported no serious damage to its system, although many telephones were out. Repairing damage to the pipe organ located in the Civic Auditorium (Civic Center) was estimated to cost $300. Air pipes broke and a portion of the organ called the harp unit fell askew when the 7,320 pipes were shaken. Scores of motorists on Bayshore Highway stopped immediately after the shock, thinking they had a flat tire. One motorist said, We felt a shuddering sidewise motion.

Location: San Francisco Schools, San Francisco, CA 94102
Description: The following reports on San Francisco schools were taken from reports received from the State Department of Public Works, Division of Architecture. None of the damage found was of such a nature that would endanger life and all the schools inspected were back in session. With the exception of two schools, Presidio Jr. High and Sheridan, where the chimneys suffered some damage, and the San Francisco City College, where some ceramic facing tiles fell off, all the damage observed consisted of cracked plaster on furred walls and fallen portions of plastered ceilings, particularly in buildings having wood lath. It can be generally stated that schools built prior to the Field Act suffered greater damage than those built after 1933. Most of the modern schools went through the earthquake practically unscathed. The following schools were selected for inspection after discussions with city officials brought out the fact that most of the damage was reported from schools falling in a line roughly paralleling the San Andreas Fault.

Location: Presidio Jr. High, 29th Ave and Clement St, San Francisco, CA 94121
Description: Three-story reinforced-concrete and steel-frame structure. A r.c. chimney rises about 35 feet above roof. Ornamentations atop this chimney became loose and fell off. One piece, weighing about 350 lbs., fell into the paved court and another fell through the skylights on the top floor which, being of r.c. flat slab construction, suffered no damage. The chimney proper, probably r.c., does not show any sign of damage. An old vertical crack through the concrete wall showed at the junction of two wings of the building. Horizontal and 45° shear cracks appeared in the plaster of the stairwell.

Location: George Washington High School, 31st Ave, between Geary and Balboa, San Francisco, CA 94121
Description: Three-story r.c. structure, built in 1936. The school has large window openings. Music room and auditorium added in 1952. No damage. Hardly any plaster cracks.

Location: Abraham Lincoln High School, 22nd Ave, between Quintara and Santiago, San Francisco, CA 94116
Description: A substantial r.c. building, first built in 1940 with addition in 1952. The only noticeable damage was some slight cracks in the stairwells at floor levels.

Location: City College, Phelan Ave and Ocean Ave, San Francisco, CA 94112
Description: The Science building, built in 1940, has ceramic tile facing. This veneer, near the NE corner of the building, broke loose and fell off over an area of 4' x 8' (approx.). Some fractured tiles numbering three or four and a few other tiles bulged out. No other damage was reported.

Location: Farragut School, between Capitol and Faxon Ave, San Francisco, CA 94112
Description: This school is a stuccoed-wood-frame building, built in 1911, with r.c. walls up to the elevated first floor level. Extensive plaster cracks, particularly in the stairwells at the junction of the plastered stud wall and concrete. On the exterior the corners of what appeared to be a bond beam at the top of the elevated first floor showed spalling.

Location: Sheridan School, at Capitol and Farallones St, San Francisco, CA 94112
Description: Three-story stuccoed-wood-frame building, built in 1909, with r.c. walls up to the elevated first floor level. This building is practically identical with the Farragut School. Extensive plaster damage was noted, particularly in the stair walls, running horizontally. A 14-foot-high brick chimney tied together with angle irons fell off in sections. One bracing strut in the attic space broke, probably as a result of the impact suffered when the chimney hit the roof. Plaster ceiling was also damaged. It was also noticed that an empty water tank in the attic broke loose from its pipe connections.

Location: Longfellow School, at Lowell St, near Mission, San Francisco, CA 94110
Description: Built about 1907. First story r.c.; second story wood-frame. This school is just about to be replaced by a new building. The stairwell shows extensive horizontal cracks. There were also sizeable vertical cracks in the plastered stud wall partitions and ceilings.

Location: West Portal School, Taraval St, Claremont Blvd, and Lenox Way, San Francisco, CA 94127
Description: Two-story-type 1/b structure, built in 1927 and rehabilitated in 1932. Reinforced-concrete building. Numerous cracks in the corridor walls in horizontal and vertical directions. Most of the cracks, however, must have been in existence for some time and should be attributed to the result of continuous earth movement rather than to the effect of the recent earthquakes. There is a large old crack through the terraced yard and through the r.c. retaining walls. This crack roughly follows the center line of the streetcar tunnel which lies underneath. A few classroom doors are out of alignment and bind.

Location: Lowell High School, at Masonic and Hayes, San Francisco, CA 94117
Description: Three-story-type III, r.c. and brick veneer building, built in 1912, rehabilitated in 1935. The corridors have been strengthened by struts. There are numerous cracks in the plaster along and around these struts. Horizontal cracks in the stairwell at floor levels. Plaster fell in sizeable chunks off the classroom ceilings in library, chemistry laboratory, and auditorium. These floors are very springy, and the plaster is on wood lath (with the exception of the rehabilitation work which was done with exp. metal lath). One vertical crack was observed through the center of the brick veneered pilaster on the west side of the Hayes Street facade.

Location: James Lick Jr. High, at Noe and 25th Sts, San Francisco, CA 94110
Description: Built in 1933. This three-story building suffered hardly any damage. Very few plaster cracks.

No building sustained structural damage. Damage consisted mainly of plaster and window cracking. Approximately 70-80 windows in exterior sash required replacement. Continuous ground crack around the perimeter of one building. The crack was about 1/8 inch wide and about 6 feet away from the face of the building. Estimated cost of repairs to all buildings, $26,530, with $17,400 of the total cost required for the Library Building.

Location: California Academy of Sciences, 55 Music Concourse Dr, San Francisco, CA 94118
Description: Motion rapid, lasted 1-1½ minutes. Direction NE and E-W. Felt by and frightened all. Loud earth noises heard. Shop machines rattled. Hanging objects swung. Books and electrical parts fell. Damage slight.

Location: California Academy of Sciences, 55 Music Concourse Dr, San Francisco, CA 94118
Description: Plaster damage in Dioramas in west wing (North American Wing). Plaster cracked at juncture of Diorama walls to roof beam. There was some debris on the skylights of the Dioramas which was thought to be paint flakes and plaster shaken loose by the shock. There was a very small crack, 3 inches long, in the bottom of the plate glass of the second Diorama from the entry in the main lobby. There was a small spalled spot on the tail of the plaster model of the thresher shark in the display room at the northeast corner of the building. There is a statue outside the building near the northeast corner with a roof supported by four columns. One column cap was badly cracked and several columns were cracked.

Location: Federal Office Building, 450 Golden Gate Ave, San Francisco, CA 94102
Description: Motion rocking, rolling, generally N-S. Felt by all. Creaking of building and rattling of loose objects heard by almost everyone. Disturbed objects observed by almost everyone. Visible swaying of buildings and trees. Some plaster cracks in south walls of building. One waste water main broke. Pictures swayed; file cabinets opened to 1 foot; mercury shaken out of cistern of recording barometer; instrument console shook, mechanically providing .01 inch precipitation. General alarm; few panic stricken. Ground: Sandy.

Location: State Building, 350 McAllister St, San Francisco, CA 94102
Description: First floor - East wall of hallway cracked at juncture of western two-story addition to the six-story central wing of original building. There were four vertical cracks in this wall with some cracks having plaster spalling from them. The west wall of the eastern two-story addition to six-story central wing of the original building was cracked. The cracks occurred where partitions abut this wall. Main stairs - east and west - Partition wall cracked at the landing between the third and fourth floors. The partition runs east-west. Horizontal cracks occurred about 6 inches above the landing. There were seperation cracks between the plaster ceiling on the under-side of the stairs and the metal stair stringers. These cracks were most noticeable between the third and fourth floors but occurred to some degree between the second and fifth floors.

Location: Southern Pacific Building, 65 Market St, San Francisco, CA 94105
Description: Considerable plaster cracking and numerous windows cracked and broken throughout the building. Hollow tile walls throughout the ground floor offices cracked, some to the extent that surface plaster was removed. Some stall doors jammed in Women's Room on 6th floor.

Location: Southern Pacific Building, 65 Market St, San Francisco, CA 94105
Description: Motion rapid, lasted 1 minute. Direction vertical, then E-W. Felt by and frightened many. Windows and doors rattled; walls creaked. Hanging objects swung. Electric clock stopped. Plaster and windows cracked. Damage slight. Ground: Filled in.

Location: Southern Pacific Building, 65 Market St, San Francisco, CA 94105
Description: Very strong. Direction seemed vertical, with W-E sway. Lasted about 2-3 minutes. Excited everyone. Building moved on piling very noticeably. Lights swung wildly. Drawers in desks and cabinets slid open.

Location: Ferry Building, 1 Ferry Building, San Francisco, CA 94111
Description: Motion rapid, lasted about 10 seconds. Felt by all and frightened many on third floor (active; standing). Windows and doors rattled; building creaked. Ferry building clock stopped. Small objects and furnishings shifted. Plaster cracked. Few dishes broke. Damage slight. Ground: 120 feet bay mud.

Location: Ferry Building, 1 Ferry Building, San Francisco, CA 94111
Description: Motion rapid, lasted about 8 seconds. Direction N. Felt by all in building. Windows and doors rattled severely; building creaked severely. Hanging objects swung N. Small objects overturned. Plaster cracked. Damage slight to plaster. Ground: Pier over fill.

Location: Berry St between 3rd and 4th St, San Francisco, CA 94158
Description: Motion rapid, lasted 20 seconds. Direction E-W. Felt by and frightened all. Just stopped my car, which rocked with a rolling motion. Freight cars on spur tracks moved. No visible damage at this site.
Large plate glass window broke.
Plate glass windows broke.

Location: Merchandise Mart, 1355 Market St, San Francisco, CA 94103
Description: Considerable minor pounding damage on every floor where original building joins annex.

Location: St. Francis Hospital, 900 Hyde St, San Francisco, CA 94109
Description: Plaster cracked considerably. Small objects shifted. Ground: Soil, level.

Location: Mills Tower, 220 Bush St, San Francisco, CA 94104
Description: Motion slow, rolling, N-S, lasted 30 seconds. Loud noise like heavy thunder heard at beginning of shock. Felt by all in office building; frightened all in community. Windows, doors, and partitions rattled. Hanging objects swung N. Small objects shifted. Plaster, walls, and ceiling cracked; plaster fell. Damage slight to plaster. Two girls hysterical; several persons nauseated. Ground: Compact, level.

Location: Sansome St and Pine St, San Francisco, CA 94104
Description: Motion slow, N-S, lasted 30 seconds. Felt by all in office building; outdoors by others (active); frightened all in community. Windows and doors rattled. Hanging objects swung. Small objects shifted. Some persons become nauseated. Ground: Compact, level.

Location: Merchants Exchange Building, 465 California St, San Francisco, CA 94104
Description: Motion rapid, lasted 15 seconds. Felt by and frightened all. Windows and doors rattled; walls creaked. Plaster cracked. Damage slight. Ground: Rocky, filled in.

Motion rapid, lasted about 35 seconds. Felt by all in reinforced-concrete building; frightened few. Prolonged rattling of windows and doors; prolonged creaking of building. Plaster cracked. Ground: Rocky.

Location: Commercial Club, 465 California St, San Francisco, CA 94104
Description: Direction NE. Felt by and frightened all. Windows rattled. Small objects shifted. Ground: Level.
Direction E-W. Felt by all on 10th floor; by others outdoors (active); frightened many in community. Building rattled. Ground: Level, filled in.

Location: Post St and Grant Ave, San Francisco, CA 94108
Description: Some debris from ledges, etc. Windows shook violently.

Location: Franklin Hospital, 14th St and Noe St, San Francisco, CA 94114
Description: Motion sharp, lasted about 30 seconds. Earth noises heard by many. Felt by and frightened all. Windows, doors, and dishes rattled; building creaked. Small objects and furnishings shifted. Plaster cracked and fell. Damage slight.

Location: Stonestown Emporium, Stonestown Galleria, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Settlement of sidewalk. Plaster cracked.

Location: 360 Buckingham Way, Stonestown, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Dishes and windows broke. Plaster cracked. Refrigerator and range twisted. Damage considerable to china, glassware, mirrors, etc. Ground: Sloping.

Location: 255 Buckingham Way, Stonestown, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Dishes, windows, and furniture broke. Plaster cracked. Damage considerable to lamps, pictures, dishes, glass, and furniture. Ground: Level, filled in.

Location: Stonestown Market, Stonestown Galleria, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Dishes and windows broke. Plaster, windows, and walls cracked. Deep crack in entire ceiling. Damage considerable to concrete. Ground: Sandy soil, level.

Location: 85 Buckingham Way, Stonestown, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Small objects shifted. Dresser mirror broke. Plaster cracked. Damage slight. Ground: Filled in.

Location: Prudential Life, Stonestown, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Safe and other large objects shifted. Plaster cracked. Damage slight to plaster. Ground: Soil, compact, level.

Location: 100 Font Blvd, Apt. 11-L, Parkmerced, San Francisco, CA 94132

Location: 22 Fuente Ave, Parkmerced, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Furnishings shifted. Dishes broke. Plaster and walls cracked. Damage slight to concrete. Ground: Sandy, level and sloping; filled in.

Location: Parkmerced Towers, 3711 19th Ave, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Furnishings shifted. Plaster cracked. Damage slight. Ground: Soil, compact, sloping.

Location: 405 Serrano Dr, Parkmerced Tower Apartments, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Glassware, pictures, etc., shifted. Dishes broke. Plaster cracked. Damage slight. Ground: Probably soil, level.

Location: 131 Bucareli Dr, Parkmerced, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Small objects shifted. Plaster cracked. Damage slight. Ground: Soil, compact, level.
Small objects and furnishings shifted. Plaster and walls cracked. Damage slight.

Location: 120 Serrano Dr, Parkmerced, San Francisco, CA 94132
Description: Small objects shifted. Plaster cracked. Damage very slight. Ground: Compact, level.

Motion rapid. Motion N-S and up and down. Felt by and awakened observer on first floor of weakly built wooden house. Windows, doors, and dishes rattled; house creaked. Hanging objects swung. Small objects shifted; vases overturned; knickknacks fell. Dishes and one vase broke. Damage slight. Dog terrified. Ground: Sandy, steep.
Two-story wooden back stairs collapsed.
Large amount of canned goods fell in store.

Motion rapid. Felt by and frightened all. Windows, doors, and dishes rattled; house creaked. Small objects and furnishings shifted; vases and small objects overturned; knickknacks, books, and pictures fell. Ground: Compact.
Motion rapid, lasted about 30 seconds. Moderate earth noises heard. Small objects shifted. One dish broke. Small amount of plaster cracked. Ground: Sandy.

Motion rapid, lasted 30 seconds. Loud earth noises heard at beginning of shock. Felt by and frightened all in home. Windows and doors rattled. Hanging objects swung. Small objects overturned. Plaster and walls cracked. Pictures fell. Damage slight. Motion was like a spinning top, twisting and jarring, then aftershocks.

Location: Broadway and Octavia St, San Francisco, CA 94109
Description: Motion rapid, lasted 1 minute. Felt by and frightened all in home. Windows, doors, and dishes rattled; frame creaked. Doors swung. Small objects shifted and overturned. Pictures fell. Cracked plaster, and panel off of baseboards, which were distorted. Ground: Soil, sloping.
Front terrazzo stairs separated from stucco buttresses on side. Iron drainpipe on side of house bent and knocked loose from house. Ground: Soil, level.

Windows, doors, and dishes rattled. Hanging objects swung E-W. Pendulum clock facing N stopped. Trees, bushes shaken strongly. Small objects and furnishings shifted; vases, etc., small objects overturned. Plaster cracked and fell. Found minor damage at home. Floor lamps knocked over; cracks in plaster; small knickknacks broken; clock moved on mantel.

Motion rapid. Felt by all in home. Moderate earth noises heard. Windows rattled; walls creaked. Plaster cracked (most cracks old and widened a little). House (part rock and adobe) very well built. Ground: Rocky, soil.

Motion slow after first jerk, lasted 15-20 seconds. Felt by all; frightened all in home. House creaked so loudly could not have heard earth noises. Windows, doors, and dishes rattled. Hanging objects swung E-W. Small objects shifted; vases and small objects overturned; knickknacks and books fell from inside walls. Dishes broke. Damage slight.

Location: 265 Santa Clara Ave, San Francisco, CA 94127
Description: Motion slow, lasted 5 seconds. Direction S-N. Loud earth noises from S-N heard by many. Felt by many; frightened many in home. Windows, doors, and dishes rattled; house creaked. Hanging objects swung S-N. Trees, bushes shaken moderately. Small objects and furnishings shifted; small objects overturned. Plaster cracked. Knickknacks, books, pictures, and plaster fell. Slight amount of dish and window breakage. Damage slight. Following shocks seemed to be jolts with no compass directions. Ground: Compact, sloping.

Arrived home to find ornaments such as vases and knickknacks thrown across the room in a NE direction. Contents of bathroom cabinet fell out and door closed. Phonograph moved 8 inches from wall. Stairwell seemed to have sunk 1/4 inch. Second step down from front door chipped and cement at side of joint broken loose. Some loose plaster bits on stairs and in hall. Damage slight. Building wood-frame; two stories above garage.

Motion rapid, lasted 30 seconds. Loud earth noises heard by many 3 seconds before shock. Felt by and frightened all in home. Windows, doors, and dishes rattled; house creaked. Hanging objects swung. Furnishings shifted; vases and small objects overturned. Plaster and walls cracked. Knickknacks, books, pictures, and plaster fell. Dishes broke. Damage slight. Ground: Loose, sandy.

Motion jolting, then moderate shaking, lasted 1-2 minutes. Loud earth noises heard. Small objects fell from shelves. Bookcases and T.V. moved. Spring in 400-day clock broke; vases, bottle, and electric light on front porch broke. Ground: Sandy, sloping.

Location: 143 Brunswick St, Crocker-Amazon District, San Francisco, CA 94112
Description: Motion rapid, eased off, then strong shaking. Moderate earth noises heard. Small objects shifted. Dishes broke. Plaster cracked. Damage considerable. Ground: Compact, sloping.

Motion rapid, lasted 2 minutes. Direction W. Moderate earth noises from W heard by many. Felt by all; frightened few. Windows rattled; walls creaked. Hanging objects swung W. Small objects and furnishings shifted. Plaster, windows, walls cracked. Knickknacks, books, and plaster fell. Windows broke. Damage considerable. Ground: Rocky, compact, level.

Motion slow, lasted few seconds. Direction S-N. Loud earth noises from S-N heard by many. Felt by observer (active) on first floor of strongly built brick building (store); frightened many. Windows rattled. Pendulum clock stopped. All grocery merchandise fell off shelves. Store closed for five hours. Damage about $1,500. Ground: Soil, level.
Vases overturned; knickknacks fell. Plaster and walls cracked. Damage slight.

Ground: Rocky, sloping; shelf cut in hill of rock; cement floor on rock bed.

The earthquake was very intense, gathering great force with a giant jack hammer effect and with a slithering motion like a car with locked brakes going into a side slide. No warning rumble; rumble heard when shock reached peak shake. Lamps, knickknacks, china, and groceries all spewed out. My heavy oak china cabinet and massive table moved 2-3 inches away from original position; kitchen stove moved 2 inches; furnace in basement moved 2 inches off base and water heater tilted off base. Living room outer wall buckled. Plasterboard cracked throughout house, also outside plaster. Basement floor cracks look like a spider web. Electric wires outside snapped in two. Everything in our home was in a shambles. Constant tremors from 8:38 A.M. on Friday to 12:05 Sunday night, with one small tremor Monday morning. We are located at Junipero and Alemany Blvds. Ground: Soil, compact, slightly sloping.

Location: 2611 San Jose Ave, San Francisco, CA 94112
Description: The Safeway store is the one from my house going in the direction of Daly City, past the part where railroad crosses street. My 3-year-old daughter and I were at the store when shock occurred. There was a smell of gas. My children said there was the same smell at St. Michael's School. As soon as one smelt the gas it really began to shake. The ground seemed to rise up and down and the most awful roar - something so different from all other sounds - came with this movement. Store seemed to rock and roll several times, then shake very hard. Glass, food, etc., flew. People ran; some panicky. Others, like myself, didn't know if it was an explosion or shock until we went outside. As I ran home I saw other damage. In our apartment one room had no damage, while four others either had large cracks over walls or complete breaks and fallen plaster. Pictures, etc., flew and bathroom was a mess, everything broke. As soon as we went inside the house we felt more movement of the house and ground in the backyard and heard noises and rumbles. This kept on all the rest of the day and night. All we did was come in and run out.
Furnishings shifted. Dishes broke. Plaster cracked in kitchen. Damage considerable. All closed doors opened. Ground: Soil, compact, level.

Second floor. Figurines broke. Lamp fell from nightstand. Clothing thrown from closet and shelves. Trim on dressing table broke off and found in middle of floor (nails still in it). Canned goods in storage closet thrown out and dented. Cupboard doors opened, causing glass stemware to fall and break. Kitchen service table pushed to center of room. Stove knob fell off and was found in corner of room. About an 8-inch wall crack over window. Ground: Soil, level.

Furniture moved from walls. Many objects thrown to floor. Juices spilled in refrigerator. I ran out the back way and heard my neighbor two doors away screaming. When I ran out to backyard, I found the earth was moving away from me, like an escalator. It moved so rapidly it made me dizzy and sick. The building kept on creaking for sometime afterwards, as if settling. I believe the tile in the bathroom has settled about 1/32 inch. Ground: Compact, level, sloping.

Store. Packing stripped loose from plumbing pipes in rear of building. Water ran out in buckets full and went all through the floor and ceiling of room below. Plaster on ceilings and walls loosened by shock and soaked with water.
Ceiling cracked in two places. Gas line broke in two places. Ground: Solid rock; slight hill.

It was the most terrifying experience of my life. House shook. Cupboards, oven, and refrigerator doors flew open. Knickknacks and pictures fell, some broke. I ran to rear of house. Patio shook; flower pot broke. Ground: Soil, sloping.

The noise of great hammer blows was terrific. Everything rattled and swayed. My unbelieving eyes saw my grand piano dancing a jig - seemed to rise up off the floor. All of the shocks were felt here, including a continued slight trembling on Saturday in p.m. No rolling motion. Mid-forenoon shock on 22nd sounded as if a big truck had crashed into house. Ground: Soil, compact, level.

Few plaster cracks; three window cracks. Picture fell and broke; several potted plants fell and broke; one glass broke; small bottles thrown from medicine chest and few broke. Description: Two slight cracks in plaster walls on each side of stairs leading to basement. New terrazzo step cracked. Gas meter twisted forward, with slight leak at joint. Slight settlement of foundation. I was thrown around and around in circles. Other shocks quite severe. Shocks have continued incessantly day and night. Damage slight. Ground: Sandy, rocky; house on steep incline.

House shook violently. Coffee spouted into the air from a cup that didn't turn over. Loud rumble virtually drowned out the sound of crashing dishes, breaking bottles, etc. Heavy refrigerator facing north moved 1½ feet away from south wall and swung west in more than a 30° angle. Stucco foundation chipped and cracked. Sounds from the aftershocks seem to come from west-east before the jerking and twisting motion. Aftershocks are still being felt (March 27).

Small objects and furnishings shifted. Dishes broke. Walls and ceilings cracked. Damage slight. Separated plumbing under kitchen sink (south side of house). Sheet rock did not do as well as plastered walls. Did not roll a long time after major shake. Just a quick, hard shake. Some of the little shocks have been pretty sharp and quick, and can be heard before they are felt. Ground: Soil, loose, sloping.

When the big shock came, the only noise we heard was the joists, or the frame of the house, breaking up. It's a two-story house and I thought it would collapse bofore we got out. I didn't notice any particular direction, but the description I read in the parer of a 'dust man chalen out' is most apt, to us. A solt shtor and a bottle of after shave lotion were the only things that fell, but our cquare grand piano moved 2 inches. Our house is built on sandy soil and is about 33 years old. The collings were cracked at one time but were painted over. The paint is still intact.

Shoemaker said his machine rolled back and forth. On Hill Street (level) bookcase moved away from wall. Description: My T.V. was at the foot of my bed on a table about 6 inches higher than bed. I fell to the floor and the T.V. hit the bed where I'd been. The place shook like a freight train going through. Two lamps fell and a bookcase fell forward. Every-thing in refrigerator was a mess. The subsequent tremors vere enough to make me a little jumpy, so I put everything on the floor. Dishes broke. Plaster cracked. Damage slight.

Minor shocks were felt, accompanied by earth noises, at frequent intervals until seven o'clock. From about ten o'clock until midnight minor tremors were felt hourly. A heavy jolt about mid-night activated mercury switches again. Minor tremors were felt occasionally until Sunday night, the 24th. Ground: Soil, compact, sloping.

Location: Shell Bldg, 100 Bush St, San Francisco, CA 94104
Description: Slight paint flaking at existing cracks. One light fixture in general office area (5th floor) in south bays dropped slightly. It was reported that chimes in old grandfather clock were set in motion. Slight movement was noted along existing crack in partition in southeast corner of building off lobby on first floor. Crack occurs along juncture of partition to column. Light fixture at ceiling reported to have shifted slightly. 100 Bush Street: Existing crack at juncture of partition to south wall column opened. This was the most notable damage. In the subbasement a slight leak developed in the 8-inch main steam line at the point where the hori-zontal line joins the tee fitting to the main riser. The repairs consisted of replacing the gasket, which had been in service 27 years. Top of building: Wedges shimming wood flagpole, where it passes through roof of small tower structure, dropped out. This may have occurred during the earthquake or they may have worked loose prior to the earth-quake. Essentially no damage to the building. No damage noted in building adjoining to the north (465 Battery St.).

Ground: Soil, sand, clay, compact, level.

Heard low-pitched earth noise for at least 2 seconds before I felt any motion. Then the house vibrated at such a rapid rate I first thought that something had broken in one of the appliance motors around the house and that the vibration was caused by a motor running with unbalanced shaft. Frying pan on the burner of a built-in electric range (mounted on a wall about 4 feet above a concrete foundation) made a terrific noise and seemed to jump up and down, but chairs and tables supported by a more springy wooden floor did not. I concluded from this that the vertical component of acceleration came very close to 'g.' The frequency was not far from the pitch of the lowest note on a piano, and I would say that a vertical motion of perhaps 15-20 cycles/sec and amplitude of nearly a half-millimeter would account quite well for what was noticed in the house. The duration seemed about 30 seconds; however, I imagine it was really closer to 5 seconds. As soon as I realized it was an earthquake, I decided to watch the water in a swimming pool just outside the house. By this time the vibrations had slowed down somewhat, and the surface of the water was covered with small waves (wave length perhaps 4 inches) moving in a N-S direction; so it seems that the initial motion also had a N-S component. There was a period of a few seconds of comparative quiet, then a very much slower E-W motion started, which set up waves on the pool with a wave length of perhaps 4 feet and an amplitude of nearly 3 inches, almost splashing the water over the coping. The pool is 36 feet long in the E-W direction. Motion of the water in the pool could still be seen 20 minutes later.

Shaking preceded by rumbling sound, as though a huge truck were passing by, then in accompaniment with the noise, which grew louder and louder, things started to vibrate, slowly at first, then harder, until I felt thoroughly shaken. It all diminished with a slower motion. I was not conscious of any direction. My son was outdoors and said the house 'wiggled awful.' House is on firm, level ground, very compact, even though situated right next to a creek. Rumbling seemed to come up from the ground. In some rooms nothing moved; in others, almost everything moved. For the most part, objects along outside walls didn't move at all, while objects on the inside walls did. Plaster cracked on inside walls only. One crack had a corresponding crack in the next room but did not actually go all the way through the wall. Felt no twisting sensation at all. No chimneys or uprights fell. Foundations, walls, etc., are in good shape. The only damage was to plaster and small objects which fell.

Motion rapid, lasted 3-4 seconds. Loud earth noises heard. The ground under our house undulated violently in a strong W-E motion. The roof sounded like it was being torn completely off. Small objects seemed to bounce. The shade on a large lamp was displaced but the lamp did not fall. I was looking at a huge picture that hangs on the inside wall of the living room. It swung out from the wall from the bottom to a distance of about 6 inches but did not tilt at any angle when it stopped moving. All other pictures and mirrors in the house were tilted. The noise was astonishingly loud and sounded like a swiftly moving train had suddenly run under the house. Noise was unlike any sound I have ever heard. As far as we can determine, there was no damage, not even any new cracks. Our house is made of concrete blocks, 8 inches thick, reinforced with steel rods, and built off the ground about 3 feet. One other interesting fact which I noticed was that three large dishes, which I keep on top of a fence for the birds drinking water, were not disturbed in any way, but only the day before, all three were knocked to the ground by the sonic boom that was felt and heard here in Novato. Ground: Soil, compact, level.

Location: Telephone structure, 15th and Franklin Sts., Oakland, CA 94612
Description: Press reported Oakland's tallest building, the telephone structure at 15th and Franklin Sts., swayed like a tree.
Hundreds of persons at the Leamington Hotel sought safety beneath doorways, or rushed headlong into the streets.

Location: Oakland Veterans Administration Hospital, Oakland, CA 94612
Description: Large cracks appeared in the outside walls of the Oakland Veterans Administration Hospital.

Location: Various grocery stores and supermarkets, Alameda and Contra Costa Counties, CA
Description: Almost every grocery store and supermarket throughout the two counties (Alameda and Contra Costa) reported masses of toppled canned goods.
Two giant skylight windowpanes in the Highland Hospital surgery broke.

Location: Town House, 20th and Broadway, Oakland, CA 94612
Description: upper-story windows of the Town House, 20th and Broadway, broke.
Minor plaster cracking.

All Oakland schools, except those consisting entirely of portable buildings, were inspected. Only very minor cracking seemed to have occurred in State approved schools. In a few cases, extensive cracking occurred in a few unapproved school structures such as Emerson, Hoover Jr. High, Oakland Junior College (Merritt), Santa Fe, and Wilson (Academic Building). In many cases it was questionable whether the cracks were due to settlement or shrinkage or whether they were caused by the earthquake.
Cracks in wood ceiling beams. Plaster cracks in Art Room hall.
Small break under sun deck at NW corner of building. Plaster crack in Room 30 at window. Plaster crack at transom at west end of upper corridor.
Horizontal crack on outside of building near Auditorium entrance.
Old 2-story building. Cracks around skylights in second story corridors.
Room 24: Old plaster crack opened up. Room 15: Crack across back of room and plaster crack on wall opposite entrance to room.

Cornice cracked in foyer. Plaster badly cracked in teachers' rest room and lunch room. Teachers' toilet (east side of building): Plaster fell, some loose. Traffic patrol room: Plaster loose. Tile on gable end (rear of building) had appearance of being loose. Tile at southwest corner appeared broken. On rear of building wall was cracked over windows of Room 14 and boys' and girls' toilets.
Many plaster cracks which appear to be shrinkage cracks.
Loose plaster in Room 120.

Room 1 (NW corner): Crack in plaster. Room 7 (SW corner): Plaster crack from ceiling to floor, also shows on stairwell side. Southwest corner on exterior: Half-timber is loose. Room 5 (NE corner): Crack from ceiling to floor. Kindergarten Terrace (S side): Horizontal crack below floor.
Plaster soffit on west side of Kindergarten - piece fell off. Cracks in corridor near Rooms 2 and 3.

Location: Hoover Jr. High School, Oakland, CA 94609
Description: Old break in wall between Shop and Girls' Gymnasium seemed to have opened up. Plaster cracks in Rooms 34 and 36.
Annex: Cracks reopened in northeast corner.
Plaster crack at ceiling beam between lobby and corridor. Cracks at corridor entrances to stage and cafeteria.
Loose plaster in Room 16. Plaster cracks in stairway at west end. Rooms 1, 3, 4: Plaster cracks showed signs of opening up.
Classroom and Auditorium Building: Roof tile on north of Auditorium looked loose where it projects beyond gutter.
Run plaster molding over main entrance loosened.
Crack on exterior through two stories at junction of Auditorium and north wing (cause of this crack doubtful since there were no fragments of stucco on ground).
Plaster crack in wall and tile wainscot near custodian's room near staff dining room. Plaster crack in corridor near Rooms 210, 211, 212.

Academic Building: Bulging plaster on ceiling in Room 49. Bulging plaster in men's toilet in rear of corridor. Pieces of cast cement on terrace floor at entrance to Auditorium (may have dropped from columns and pilasters).
Some plaster appeared loosened in ceiling of Auditorium.
Main Academic Building: Loose brick in entrance arch to Auditorium. Crack in arcade near street entrance. Classroom Annex: Crack in one of the arcade arches.
Crack in concrete wall west of main entrance.

Crack in southwest corner of dining room. Cast stone capitals over main entrance showed a very wide joint at base. Crack in concrete wall at west stage entrance. Room 13: Crack in plaster. Library: Crack in plaster. Second floor corridor: Plaster cracks in southwest corner. Girls' toilet (second floor): Plaster cracks. Stair Hall (northeast corner): Horizontal crack above landing. Same stair - crack at head of stair on left side. Room 10 (northeast corner): Bulge in plaster. Girls' gymnasium (southwest corner): Crack in concrete wall, also cracks in south wall. Room 54: Bulges in plaster ceiling.

Location: Intersection of Woodside Road and Massachusetts Ave., Redwood City, CA 94061
Description: Very definite ground waves as indicated by overhead electric wires and telephone cables. Those running parallel to Massachusetts Avenue alternately sagged very low then snapped taut. I saw this repeated twice; may have occurred again, but I failed to observe it. Utility lines on Woodside Road did not move with the sagging-stretching motion, but swayed from side to side. No foreshocks noticed; some subsequent ones noticed but time not recorded.
Motion rapid, lasted at least 2 minutes. Loud earth noises heard. Small objects shifted. Cement garage floor cracked. Ground: Rocky, steep.

Motion rapid. Moderate earth noises heard by many. Felt by all and frightened many in community. Windows, doors, and dishes rattled; house creaked. Hanging objects swung. Electric clock facing NE stopped. Small objects shifted and overturned. Plaster, windows, and walls cracked. Knickknacks and books fell. Dishes and windows broke. Damage considerable. No damage to the post office but across the street houses were damaged by cracking plaster, and many articles were thrown from shelves and walls. Some homes in the community were badly affected, others not at all. My home shows no damage and very few objects fell from the shelves. The post office (built on cement) creaked, but there was no shifting of furniture, fixtures, or even small articles.
Press reported cosmetic bottles broke in beauty salon; wall mirror broke in barber shop; acoustical ceiling cracked in real estate office.

Sounds preceded motion by about 5 seconds. Motion was gentle, large amplitude, and sort of circular. Trees outside of window (in leaf) made a sort of swishing sound. Motion felt continuously for about 12 seconds by observer and others questioned. Ground: Sandy.

Press reported this was the strongest shock felt in Santa Rosa since 1906. Frightened and excited persons jammed telephone switchboards with calls. At the 49-year-old County Courthouse hundreds of fine paint cracks (stated to be new) were found in an outer wall of an old two-level vault in the County Administrator's office. A large globe-like lighting fixture hanging from a chain over a top-floor stairwell swung for 5 minutes after the shock; swinging courtroom doors flapped. Liquor display fell in one store. In another store dress racks looked like they would fall. Many ran to the streets in downtown and residential areas, and many suffered dizzy spells.

Motion rapid, lasted 30 seconds. Direction E-W. Faint earth noises heard by few. Felt by all in community; frightened few. Windows, doors, and dishes rattled. Pendulum clocks facing E stopped. Trees, bushes shaken strongly. Small objects overturned; knickknacks and books fell. Damage slight. Ground: All kinds.

The roll seemed to go from S-N. The house shuddered violently and as the floor rolled, the walls appeared to be moving up and down. I looked up over my head and saw the kitchen wall above a door cracking. The entire house made a tremendous cracking noise. Plate glass mirror, about 6 by 4 feet, over fireplace was knocked loose from wall and broke into hundreds of pieces. One living room window cracked. All lamps in living room fell to floor and most of the books in floor-to-ceiling bookcase on the floor. Plaster cracked in every room of seven-room house; some fell from upstairs walls; windows cracked. Heavy bureau moved about 2 feet. Our neighbor's house suffered damage about the same as our house, but people across the street didn't even have a tilted picture. Our house is a two-story shingle house, built about 1905.

Press reported there were many minor fires, gas leaks, broken water pipes, and broken chimneys, but damage was minor. Windows broke at various locations. Cornice atop the Metropolitan Hotel, Linden and Grand Avenues, was loosened and finally removed. Groceries and liquor fell from shelves in supermarkets. At Kaiser Foundation Hospital only two minor injuries were reported.

Motion moderate. Faint earth noises heard. Ground: Soil, compact.
Motion rapid, lasted 20-35 seconds. Small objects shifted. Plaster cracked. Damage slight to plaster. Ground: Soil, compact, sloping.
Motion rapid, lasted 5-10 seconds. Moderate earth noises heard. Small objects shifted.
